# Abstract

Fog computing is the next generation in the Cloud computing paradigm. It has emerged as a promising technology that can bring the IoT device closer to the cloud network. In a practical sense, the fog&#39;s role is to collaborate with the Cloud instead of replacing it. It does this by processing the data that is sent by the IoT within the fog and then sent to the cloud for additional computations and storage. There are many benefits to this model because it reduces the time involved in the process and it is more efficient for the cloud as it reduces load. Because the Fog has various characteristics that differ from modern computing paradigms such as the ability to transfer data through a geographical distribution. This will allow the fog to be more flexible than the cloud since thousands of fog nodes can be placed across the city. This interoperability brings in the notion of having accurate and seamless support for real-time services that a centralized cloud would not be able to bring about. Fog computing also boasts its privacy dominance in the cloud market place. Fog machines can be purchased for private use for companies and even individuals that can allow the processing of data to happen in the local level, so the concern of sensitive data being analysed by an outside corporation will be diminished. However, just like the Cloud, the Fog also has downfalls. Two in particular are the storage issues and the capability to process big complex data. The cloud can have almost infinite storage with powerful capabilities that aims for long-term deep analysis because of its architecture while the fog performs short-term edge analysis due to its instant responsiveness.

The purpose of this paper is to investigates these advantages/disadvantages of both the cloud and fog systems in the area of data transfer across IoT devices to these technologies. This is done by listing different forms of collaborations that can be used and deciding which form of collaboration would be best for different criterions such as for privacy, sensitivity, storage etc. To help support the research, the development of a Java program was created that uses fuzzy logic as an approach to computing based on the &#39;degrees of truth&#39; rather than being true or false. Having this form of logic allows for the user to set their levels of criterions and a recommendation would be printed out

The second phase of this research involves the use of transactional properties that are referred to as pivot, retriable and compensatable. These transactional properties&#39; purpose is to allow people to view the execution behaviours of an application such as if the process has passed or failed. These transactional properties are usually dedicated to web services and databases but this research borrows them for the use in IoT devices.  In addition, how they comply with the duties of IoT. These duties consist of sensing the data, actuating that data and then communicating the data. This research will designate these transactional properties in each duty to find which would be the most appropriate. The second phase of the Java program also consists of two different models to support this research, one which allows the user to interact with the program to find the appropriate transactional property by choosing single/multiple duties. Lastly, a new form of pivot for the vital support in the IoT is introduced and can be experimented with in the Program.



**Keywords.** Cloud, Fog, IoT, Transactional-properties, Pivot, Java, Coordination

# Chapter 1: Introduction

Cloud computing has become a world phenomenon from the first year it was conceived. It has shown to become essential for organisations and businesses to deploy. Because of the success of cloud computing, there has become large demand for further advancement in this area of technology. This has shown to be evident when looking at the rise of data that has been generated in these years [CITATION Hon17 \l 2057] the amount of connected Internet of things devices has grown from 15.41 billion in 2015 to 26.66 billion in 2019 and are expected to rise even further by 2020.1 Cloud storage is not enough to deal effectively with this level of expansion. Such staggering numbers of IoT devices bring about many issues, such as internet delay, network congestion and aggravating buffering spikes when receiving data. The sole use of cloud has shown to have performance instability, especially to massive organisations that hold masses of customers. These customers expect 100% availability for the price they pay from companies such as Amazon. [CITATION Isl13 \l 2057] However, this does not come into fruition because of the severe performance instability during high load. In fact, there have been researchers that have conducted an experiment to stress test2 Google, Microsoft and Amazon of their cloud performance to show their service availability, the results show response time varied by a factor of 20 at different points in the day. [CITATION Hof10 \l 2057] These latency issues are seen to increase as more devices become interconnected.

Fog computing serves as a solution to the problems mentioned, as it provides the IoT device the storage, computation, load-share and networking resources. Fog computing moves to reduce the service delay for both the applications being used and the end-user, while the cloud is needed to provide the extensive computation, big data and the storage capacity with more latency levels. Thus, making it a requirement to understand the interplay between the cloud and fog.[CITATION You17 \l 2057] Although the power of the cloud is maintainable enough to perform advanced network analytics and the transfer of big data, they are always too far to receive a timely response. Fog computing comes in to mitigate these issues by working the processing segment of the transfer in the data hub closer to the end-user, thus making the amount of data sent to the cloud decrease dramatically.

The utilization of fog and cloud both have their own advantages in certain areas when it comes to the regard of issues such as frequency, sensitivity, freshness, time, volume, and criticality. The goal of this paper is to discuss these parameters and what key differences should be used in certain scenarios. It will also develop a multi-criteria decision-making method using these parameters to determine which cloud and fog coordination should be used. Another segment that this paper will explore is the transactional properties that are commonly found in databases and how they would have a place in the IoT&#39;s world. This will also include a development of a program that can mirror the requirements that will be assessed in the chapters below.

### 1.5.1 - Legality Issues

As this research has shown, the cloud-fog coordination processes data locally to the user&#39;s IoT device to provide real time analysis or decisions. This processing capability requires a more complicated and costly series of edge nodes that provides these requirements. Moreover, these edge nodes receive generated data from the IoT devices, which open privacy and security concerns of those who own the data and who are responsible if data is leaked. [CITATION Rad19 \l 2057] In addition, the user data is then outsourced over the Fog node, which introduces these legality issues to the cloud. Since fog nodes are much more widespread and hard to keep track, this leaves massive holes in the security of private data, therefore it becomes more difficult to apply the privacy rules sufficiently to protect personal data about users, thus violating the Data Protection Act3. Which must make it a responsibility for organisations to ensure that data is kept protected against unlawful or unauthorised processing, access, loss or destruction.

IoT devices are also vulnerable to breaches as they continue to exchange information with each other via the internet. This relentless data collection comes with an increase in the risk of breach or failure in data security [CITATION FTC15 \l 2057]. The complexity &amp; connectivity that is found in IoT introduces new security weaknesses. The Federal Trade Commission is anxious that the expansion of proliferated cheap IoT devices and their services can create security issues for consumers in terms of data collection and purpose of usage [CITATION OBr16 \l 2057]. There is also the chance of being scrutinized as they can be used to direct denial of service (DoS) attacks on the consumer&#39;s network. These issues can because a major legal issue for IoT because it allows criminals to use an individual&#39;s data for discrimination or beneficial purposes.

### 1.5.2 – Social Issues

There is a societal concern among many citizens in the world that may not have access to the internet, thus restricting them from using the Cloud storage. This creates a challenge of accessibility, usage and acceptance. There is also clear evidence that this will become a tough boundary as Cloud storage becomes the primary method of saving, photos, videos, files and for entertainment. However, even if people become unable to access the internet, these is still the security concern, which holds true for cloud and fog storage. Perhaps the most problematic and prevalent of these security issues is identity theft, in which the personal details that are held in storage within the cloud is accessed and harvested so that they can be used for malicious purposes. This can also be done through the IoT networks.

### 1.5.3 - Ethical Issues

Cloud computing has the ability to allow clients to access on-demand services from anywhere around the globe. This level of interaction leads to exposing multiple ethical issues that is integral to pushing services and data from the user-end, fog nodes and into the data centres which typically belong to external parties. These parties create cloud infrastructures in which they have total control of the hardware. This level of restricted protection can lead to unauthorized access to data from the host that leads to many ethical issues, unlike a shared infrastructure model, where clients can use Fog (computing) machines that they own to process, store and protect the data. However, owning the infrastructure requires the client to purchase hardware, recompense operating costs and maintain software.

Through the widespread implementation of IoT sensors around the world, the existing ethical challenges they encompass becomes much more of a concern according to the social behaviour standards. The widely held argument appears around privacy of information, accuracy, and accessibility. According to [CITATION Jos09 \l 2057], the ethical behaviours of IoT entail:

- Ensuring the right to a private life
- Ensuring the integrity of information
- Ensuring access to information at any time
- Enforce property rights on information

These ethical issues, which have a clear presence in IoT, will make the boundaries between the public and private space be invisible, and individuals will not know where their information ends up and how it gets used. Surveillance type monitoring systems that utilize IoT will monitor people without their consent or awareness. These IoT surveillance type operators that are equipped with sensors would give them the capacity to &quot;hear&quot;, &quot;see&quot; and soon even &quot;smell the environment around them. The data registered by these sensors will be sent in great quantities in different passages through the networks, which, if the data is leaked then it could harm those who seek privacy. There are also technologies that allow IoT sensors to track an individual&#39;s location and movement without their knowledge by means of GPS, RFID and NFC. This could be done by tracking a chip that is implanted onto an individual for (medical reasons) and might be maliciously used for other purposes [CITATION Dan13 \l 2057].

# Chapter 2: Literature Review

## 2.1 - Introduction to Review

The vast variety of different IoT devices that are connected to the internet illuminates the depth of how these devices transfer data with each other. Records show that in 2019 the total installed IoT connected devices have risen to 26.66 million and is expected to grow up to 75.44 million by 2025. [CITATION IHS16 \l 2057]. These IoT devices has permitted both the public and organisations to combine the connected smart objects to enhance everyday human lives in many aspects[CITATION MsP14 \l 2057]. This rapid societal change has configured the way data should be processed and transferred and with the integration of cloud computing to produce new tiers of competence [CITATION Asr18 \l 2057] have stridden the way for even higher capacities in the form of fog computing to emerge. The incorporation of the cloud to the IoT field has brought upon a new way for technologies and services to control both the structured and unstructured data that ranges from within big data [CITATION Gia17 \l 2057]. However, cloud cannot continue to handle this upkeep of data that millions IoT devices are endlessly creating. The emergence of fog computing helps to mitigate this strain by moving the network resources near the IoT device. Having processing, analysing and storage of data being done in a separate device before being sent to the cloud helps alleviate the problem and reduce the computational load

## 2.2 - Overview of Cloud Computing

Cloud computing has been established in the technical world that even many corporations and governments have incorporated in their business environment. The cloud technology is built upon existing computing paradigms that inherits characteristics from pre-existing computing models. The backend of the cloud usually consists of the data storage and processing systems that are servers, which are located in remote environments.

In the modern era, it has become by default that organisations, business and other facilities to incorporate a form of cloud computing for their business and firm needs. Cloud services cater to the business needs and whims by giving a personal platform to those who would like to communicate, upload images, videos and hold important information in a shared space with other people. The advantages of cloud (in contrast to fog) extends further in areas, such as:

- **Better performance:** In contrast with the fog, the cloud is able to communicate with the IoT sensors and process that data much more efficiently, especially when dealing with big data
- **Storage capacities:** Cloud offers a much higher volume of storage than the fog. Cloud services can compromise in highly scalable and unlimited storage space that can aggregate and share the volumes of data across their services.
- **Cheaper Costs:** Since the cloud is stationed at a centralized position, it can become much cheaper to maintain than fog, which can compromise in masses of equipment, and continuous maintenance costs.

## 2.3 - Overview of Fog Computing

Fog computing is a highly virtualized platform that provides similar features as the cloud; networking storage, compute data etc. However, the main characteristic of fog is that it is created to be a networking service between the IoT end devices and the traditional cloud computing data centres. It is generally believed that fog computing is the next generation of cloud, but that would mean it would replace the cloud. This is not the case as the fog and cloud work hand-in-hand to provide enhanced efficiency and reduce the amount of data that needs to be transported. It was concluded that the cloud and fog have their own characteristics to process data, but they are a supplement to each other. However, the fog&#39;s capabilities are more advanced and performs better than the cloud when handling user requests and other emerging standards [CITATION Zha17 \l 2057].

Fog computing is part of the distributed computing paradigm that extends the services provided the cloud to facilitate tasks at a faster rate. Since the fog adds another layer in the cloud-computing paradigm, it allows for further distribution of the core functions that are usually done through the cloud, such as communication, storage, networking and control but at a closer proximity. The devices that are called fog nodes serve as the application to allow for the communication between fog and cloud. Unlike the cloud servers, the fog nodes can be deployed anywhere with an internet connection: in a household, factory floor, on a power pole, offices etc. Any devices with a computing, storage and network connectivity can be made into a fog node. These examples can be broad over many industrial controllers, switchers, embedded servers and video surveillance cameras [CITATION Cis15 \l 2057].This close proximity to the IoT device complements that amount of data that is analysed by reducing the latency and offloads in the network traffic. In fact, there has been a study by the IDC, which has estimated that the amount of data that will be analysed on devices will become physically closer to the IoT by 40%.4

### 2.3.1 - Fog Node

The fog node is one of the main components of the fog computing architecture. These nodes are generalized as both the physical and virtual component that are tightly coupled with the IoT devices or the access networks to provide the computing resources to these devices. Fog nodes are tasked to deliver geographical distribution and logical location within the context of the data cluster. In addition, the fog nodes are partly responsible of the data management and communication services between the networks of the edge layer, where the IoT device resides and the cloud service to provide a faster uplink to the data transfers. To help deploy one of the fog&#39;s capability, the fog nodes operate in a decentralized or centralized manner that can be configured to be a stand-alone fog node that communicates among each other to accomplish the task of dispersing data clusters throughout geolocations.[CITATION Mic18 \l 2057]

## 2.4 - Fog Computing Features

Fog computing possess various characteristics that differ from traditional computing paradigms. It offers many key advantages that are desired for many IoT devices that require real-time processing, fast scaling and local content resource pooling. These features have garnered a great deal of attention from both the industry and academia. Although the fog is motivated by the cloud, fog computing still has many unique characteristics that enhance the transfer of data:

**Geographical distribution:** Instead of the sole use of cloud, that offers a more centralized vision. The services and applications that are supported by fog demand a wide and geographically identifiable deployment of distribution. Such as the fog will play a big role in delivering data from trains and tracks that are equipped with sensors. Trains act as the main hub for all the data gathered from these sensors but the problem of the training moving fast can be difficult to maintain a connection with the cloud. Therefore, installing fog nodes onto the train can solve any issues with geographical distribution

**Interoperability:** Fog computing has the ability to provide accurate and seamless support for real-time services that require a fast response from the IoT device. Since the fog allows for the computation and processing of data at the network&#39;s edge which reduces the latency. This is done to allow functions to be portable between locations and reduce the processing load of the cloud server, which is usually used by many clients.

**Heterogeneity:** Fog computing allows for a variation of different data from different sources to be processed simultaneously. This is because fog comprises of heterogeneous nodes that range from sensors, IoT devices, stations and large machines in data centres. The nodes include computer-like components such as CPUs, GPUs that facility the purpose of computing on such a variety of different resources and applications[CITATION Ble17 \l 2057].

**Privacy &amp; Security Control:** The processing of data happens in the local level, so the concern of sensitive data being analysed at a shared server is alleviated. The centralized server has the risk of being vulnerable since this main hub is home to the connection of other local endpoints that make it easier for people to transfer infected files or viruses to disrupt or expose this data.

These unique characteristics all offer benefits to cloud computing paradigm. In summary, the fog is able to give assistance to the cloud by carrying the burden of massive volume of data generation from the IoT devices. It contributes to the effort of enhancing the awareness and response time to events by eliminating a round trip to the cloud for analysis.

## 2.5 Characterization Fog computing

Fog computing is a highly virtualized platform that allows for computing, storing data. The fog system is traditionally placed in the edge of the network, which serves as a link between the end devices and the cloud data center. [CITATION Fla12 \l 2057] It is true that cloud and fog share many building blocks that allow them to compute, store and access the network [CITATION Shi15 \l 2057], However, there are several unique characteristics of fog computing that were mentioned in [CITATION AnT16 \l 2057]  that make it an extension of cloud instead of a replacement. One of which is the edge location: In contrast to the cloud, the fog has a closer proximity to the end user. This feature allows the fog to provide significant advantages such as processing the data closer to the source, thus removing the barrier of any latency issues. This proximity also mitigates the cost of data transmission while at the same time reduce network congestion.[CITATION Kus19 \l 2057]

## 2.6 - Definitions of Fog

The history of fog computing is extremely limited as it is considered a broad term while still being new-fangled to the modern era. The broad scope of the fog has led to several definitions, which rely on upon different perspectives, and it has been expected that there will be many newer definitions as fog computing moves towards maturity. [CITATION AnT16 \l 2057].

_Definition 1_: Fog computing because defined as an extension of the cloud from the core to the edge of the network [CITATION Fla12 \l 2057][CITATION Das16 \l 2057]. This is the most common definition that is enforced in the technical world but there are still different variants.

_Definition 2_: [CITATION Lui14 \l 2057] states that fog computing is a scenario where a large number of heterogeneous connections ubiquitous and decentralized IoT devices communicate and potentially collaboration among them with the network to perform tasks such as processing and storing data without the invention of third parties.

_Definition 3_: Another example from [CITATION Shi15 \l 2057] explains that fog computing can become a geographically distributed everywhere with a connected resource pool which can consist of many ubiquitously connected heterogeneous edge devices that are not exclusively backed by cloud servers to provide elastic computation power, communication and storage in isolated environment to a large collection of users in the proximity.

### 2.7.1 - Fog in Smart city

Connected IoT sensors that involve applications such as processors, smart objects, controller&#39;s actuator, interconnectors and cloud networking power the concept of smart cities. [CITATION Pen17 \l 2057]These technical features all promise to change the dynamic of everything that is covered in a typical city into a more digitalized &amp; automated way. The current state of smart cities are not perfected but research by [CITATION San18 \l 2057] have curtailed the idea integrating fog computing to help plug the holes to achieve total perfection. The utilization of the fog nodes ensures that the reliability of delay-sensitive and data-intensive applications are moving in sufficient speeds that would make the smart cities flow of data much more smooth and reliable.

There have been many investigates done to evaluate the need of fog computing in world of smart living. [CITATION Jia15 \l 2057] Have developed data centralized environment that relies on the fog platform to support smart living. This is in which that followed the implementation and analysing of the flow of data that is done by EHOPES (smart energy, health, office, protection, and environmental surroundings). The paper has evaluated that the performance of the applications of the Cloud &amp; Fog topology, in which they have proved that the fog based architecture has the advantage over the EHOPES applications that are currently in place within smart cities. This reasoning is also enforced by [CITATION Yan14 \l 2057] that argued that the fog computing paradigm is the most acceptable resolve for the smart city architecture. This is because the cloud architecture alone faces many challenges such as its lack of mobility, scalability, heterogeneity and its geographical problems. [CITATION Yan14 \l 2057] States that the potential of using fog computing as the middleware between the &#39;things&#39; within the city and the cloud will improve go beyond on improving the weaknesses that were listed above. This pure fog-IoT architecture has already been discussed in many works [CITATION Das16a \l 2057][CITATION Aaz16 \l 2057].

### 2.7.2 – Fog Computing in Transport

Managing a fleet of vehicles of any kind is already fits into a computer system because of the complex process that requires geometry, algebra, statistics, abstraction and backup for preventive maintenance. However, we now see vehicles empower the use of cloud and fog computing. For example, trains are being equipped with fog nodes to act a parent for the main cloud hub. This technological achievement has allowed trains to mitigate their past incident of maintaining a solid connection to the cloud because of the train&#39;s speed. The trains benefit by using fog computing this way by giving them higher latency and faster data processing capabilities.

Vehicular ad-hoc Networks (VANET) has been introduced as an important stepping-stone for promising intelligent transportation systems. VANET consists of groups of vehicles connected by a wireless network. Before recently, this system was used to maintain safety and comfort to drivers in vehicular environments; this has been changing since the changing of vehicular ad-hoc networks that are now seen as an infrastructure for intelligent transportation system with an increasing number of autonomous vehicles on the road [CITATION Mar17 \l 2057]. After years of progress, the VANET system has been helping with ensuring traffic efficiency, safety, exchanging valuable information such as closed roads or incidents, and informing of any emergencies that have happened [CITATION Kan16 \l 2057]. Most times, VANET applications are area specific that requires to be handled locally. This makes it necessary to utilize fog computing because it moves the contents and application services to the driver&#39;s end. [CITATION Jyo18 \l 2057] Writes that fog does address the limitation of location awareness that cloud computing lacked. Such as a tourist would like to seek information on the places of interest, rather than outside cities – fog makes this possible. However, [CITATION Moh14 \l 2057] argues that fog computing still needs extensive research before its practical deployment. Yet, fog computing is still miles ahead of the traditional cloud computing method that was mentioned by [CITATION Kim15 \l 2057], that reasons fog computing can leverage computation infrastructure that is closer to the network&#39;s edge. Thereby supports applications with low latency requirements such as: Smart traffic lights, parking system, content distribution and decision support system for self-driving cars.

## 2.8 - Collaborating Cloud and Fog

The traditional cloud-based infrastructure is not nearly enough to deal with the demand the modern IoT application propose. [CITATION Kay17 \l 2057] Discusses that there are two major issues of limitation in terms of latency and bandwidth. This problem helped alleviate fog computing into the main stage by providing the means to fix these limitations by moving the data processing capabilities closer to the network&#39;s edge. [CITATION Kay17 \l 2057] Also concludes that IoT has enormous potential and therefore, to maximize it, fog and cloud are both needed. Today, many of the IoT application rely on the cloud as it usually carries almost unlimited storage and processing power. These requirements are necessary to transform the high amounts of data generated by IoT into knowledge and commands. Yet, it does not solve the mentioned issues as discussed by [CITATION Cis15a \l 2057]

Cisco has defined the concept of fog computing as an extension of the cloud to realize the full potential IoT is capable of [CITATION Cis15a \l 2057]. The selection of using cloud and fog doesn&#39;t necessary have to be binary. The two technologies together make a mutually beneficial and interdependent continuum[CITATION Pij18 \l 2057]. These interactions come in different combinations as discussed in the main section of the paper. However, the main interaction is Fog-to-Cloud, which allows the IoT system to get the best of both worlds. Sustaining the features, that cloud provides while also having the mobility of fog. Fog and cloud is able to exchange the data with each other which the data gathered by the &#39;things&#39; and sent to the cloud to process the information then distributed to various fog nodes to reach the end user.

## 2.9 - Coordination Models

Since the formation of fog computing was established, there have become different techniques for engineers to coordinate the fog between the cloud and thing. It is presented as a cloud-fog coordination configuration, which leads to different forms of interaction: {T → C}, {T → F}, {T → C|F}, {T → F → C}, {T → C → F} whereas &#39;T&#39;, &#39;C&#39;, &#39;F refers to Thing, Cloud, and Fog respectively. [CITATION Tha19 \l 2057]These coordination models all have their own advantages and disadvantages and it is up to the engineer of the IoT device to figure out which approach they want to go through the configuration to bring out the best of the IoT sensor for their certain task by determining where data should be sent. [CITATION Tha19 \l 2057]have performed an experiment on the coordination models using the 6 different criteria&#39;s (Frequency, Sensitivity, Freshness, Time, Volume, Criticality) These criteria&#39;s must be fulfilled in order to make a conclusion to which data transfer is the most suitable in the scenario.

[CITATION Tha19 \l 2057], Demonstrates that the caste study of frequency by measuring the total end-to-end latency in each coordination for streaming data continuously for a 24-hour period. The paper determined that T → F configuration consumes the least amount of time than the rest. Therefore, in conclusion, the frequency task reflects that configuration of T → F as the favourite if a client would like to rely on the rate of frequency the most in their IoT configuration. The case study of this paper will delve even deeper in all of the criteria&#39;s and discuss the best means of each coordination configuration in detail.

## 2.10 – Review of Transactional Properties in IoT

In the research field of fault tolerance for a variety of web and IoT applications, there have sprouted many ways to provide fault tolerance through difference levels. The main concept that was discussed from different publications [CITATION Joh12 \l 2057], [CITATION Had12 \l 2057], [CITATION Joc10 \l 2057] was the variety of low-level programming constructs such as exception handling which is an approach that is used to manage logical faults that are specific to each service. However, for the reliability of composite services have also been handled by higher levels of abstraction (at the execution level).  These consist of graphs, workflows and applications. Therefore, these bring upon self-regulating methods for composition of reliable composite services named the transitional properties [CITATION Omi12 \l 2057]. These transactional properties are commonly used for a service behaviour in case of failures, most notably for databases, however the main purpose these transactional properties are to ensure that the ACID (Atomicity, Consistency Isolation &amp; Durability) properties are safeguarded. [CITATION Raf15 \l 2057] Otherwise, if these properties are not considered, then they are placed as a responsibility to the client or developer.

In a typical distributed transactional method, there is a type of atomic commitment protocol (ACP) called the two-phase commit protocol (2PC). It is tasked to coordinate all the processes that participle in the transaction to either commit or abort (rollback) the transaction. It is a standard protocol used for achieving the ACID properties [CITATION Elm92 \l 2057]. Although, the 2PC protocol implements resource locking/blocking which may not be suitable for long running transactional composite services [CITATION Rub13 \l 2057]. As argued by [CITATION Rub13 \l 2057]  the researchers have developed advanced models to relax the ACID properties to allow them to compensate the completed transitions, these models consisted of SAGA transactions [CITATION Hec87 \l 2057], nested transactions[CITATION JEl85 \l 2057], open nested[CITATION Ger92 \l 2057] , split-join [CITATION Cal88 \l 2057], and Web-Tram[CITATION MYo00 \l 2057]. However, the work presented in this paper is based on the &#39;TQoS&#39; model which is ported over from the Web service activity into the IoT platform. The Transactional QoS-aware selection model builds on top of three elementary services referenced by [CITATION Had10 \l 2057]:

### 2.10.1 Review Pivot Transactional Property

The pivot transactions as said by [CITATION Mar99 \l 2057] manages the atomicity of the global transaction. For example, the global transaction is committed when the pivot transaction is committed locally. If the pivot transaction has aborted, then the transaction and all of its updates have to be compensated or not executed at all (see figure 1). The pivot service is able to imply many unique techniques such as roll-back, logs support, or reserved memory to change data on private memory that can be committed if the execution is successful. These techniques allow the pivot service to ensure atomicity in the presence of failures. For example, services that access and modify critical sensible data (e.g., financial banking information) [CITATION Yud17 \l 2057].

### 2.10.2 Review Compensatable Transactional Property

The compensatable property shares a similar execution technique with pivot, which is the &quot;all-or-nothing&quot; execution. Compensatable transactions are always executed before the pivot transaction to make it possible to compensate them if the pivot transaction cannot be committed [CITATION Kof02 \l 2057] (see figure 2). This allows it to preserve consistency, for compensation services&#39; that have to be &quot;pivot retriable&quot; which allow them to ensure full atomicity and a successful execution. Compensatable services are able to read data by default and the services that modify non-critical data can be compensated [CITATION Yud17 \l 2057]. An example of this would be if a transaction is done at one end, it does not trigger any other transaction.

### 2.10.3 Review Retriable Transactional Property

[CITATION Mar12 \l 2057] Have claimed said that retriable guarantees a successful termination after a finite number of invocations, therefore reliable service supports forward recovery (see Figure 3). [CITATION Yud17 \l 2057] Argued that implementing a retriable service can be difficult for example, a service can disappear and crash during the transition. Conversely, this introduced different techniques to alleviate this occurrence [CITATION Raf151 \l 2057][CITATION Joh121 \l 2057][CITATION Wei10 \l 2057] such as replication and substitution that can support the condition of 100% successful execution. For example, if a service is using pivot or compensatable, multiple replicas can be simultaneously invoked or it can be replaced by another functionally corresponding service if it happens to fail.

# Chapter 3: Capabilities of Fog Computing &amp; Cloud Computing

## 3.1 – Introduction

The premise of this paper is based on the survey of the creating a multi-criteria decision-making software that would help the individual decide which would be the recommend approach to handle certain data requests. The data transfers are over the fog &amp; cloud architectures and in which combination is best to handle the transfer. To determine the request, the paper bases its verdicts over six criteria&#39;s: Frequency, Sensitivity, Freshness, Time, Volume and Criticality. Both cloud and fog have their advantages over these areas and discussing this matter is the central point of this paper.

As discussed previously, fog computing is not a replacement to cloud but an extension. Both paradigms have their own advantages, but they can also collaborate with each other to improve overall efficiency for certain responsibilities. Below will explain the parameters in detail and in which category of coordination would be needed to accomplish these levels of tasks.

## 3.2 - Frequency

Frequency criteria depends on the occurrence of a number of data being transferred over a certain time. The frequency the data travels to both the cloud and fog are determined by the application that sends and receives the data. There are different types of data aggregation for the transfer of data, these could include the regular frequency type, which sends data dependent on a normal file transfer, or there is live video streaming which requires streamline output of data without any interruptions. The distance between the end points also come into play. The fog nodes dominate as the architecture is segregated across geolocations while the cloud is centralized. This form of transfer allows fog to eliminate the delays in the data transfer since the data is kept closer to the user instead of remote data centres[CITATION Kum15 \l 2057].

## 3.3 - Sensitivity

The sensitivity criteria fall within the privacy area of data and how protected it is against unwarranted disclosure. Accessing sensitive data should always have a form of safeguard, which is usually supported by legal and ethical reasons pertaining to private, personal and proprietary considerations. Privacy of sensitive information has always been a top concern for many individuals and corporations that hold massive amounts of confidential information about their clients and employees that should be legally kept undisclosed. Data security has always been a major hurdle for technologies, but it is typically known for uncontrolled environment like the cloud to pose many challenges in this capacity [CITATION Lyn18 \l 2057]. These challenges are associated with the cloud&#39;s openly shared distributed environments that become vulnerable through these characteristics:

- The data is stored inside a third party server that is at a remote destination.
- The physical servers that hold the data are shared between other users; therefore, the security portion is placed on a software-level only.
- The individual&#39;s data can be accessed via the open internet, thus become vulnerable to hackers.

These reasons are a major motive for companies to turn to fog technology. The advances of fog nodes allow the data to be closer to home instead of the edge of the network; this alone covers the detriments of cloud which hold the information at a remote network while being shared with other users. Fog also supports a new layer of protection that enables attacks to become easily detectable and provide real-time incident response services that enable IoT devices to respond to breaches without disrupting the service simultaneously.

## 3.4 - Freshness

The freshness criteria refer to the refresh rate of the updated data, as referenced by Adrian Perrig: &quot;The data freshness implies that the data is recent and ensures that there are no adversary replayed old data&quot;. It asks the question if the data is fresh enough for the user&#39;s expectations or if the data is the most recent version. Data freshness uses multiple metrics and forms of quality factors, that all have an aspect of freshness, for that reason, freshness is commonly known as a quality dimension [CITATION Mat99 \l 2057]. Each of the factors are suite for a particular problem for an IoT device. For example, in a system that relies of replication, the number of refresh operations that have been applied to a relation in order to reflect the changes made in a master relation is an excellent freshness metric. However, in a data-warehousing scheme, the time passed from the update of a message to its delivery may be even more significant. The two quality factors of the freshness criteria are defined as:

- **Currency Factor** : The currency factor represents how &quot;stale&quot; the data is with the respect of its sources. It is recommended to use the least-most expired form of data to be delivered to the users. It is important to acknowledge that data, which is outdated, can cause confusion to the user and even the system reading it, since the data may have changed since the extraction.[CITATION Seg90 \l 2057] The goal is to return the same type of data that was stored in the server so the currency metric captures the gap between the data extraction and the data of the delivery. For example, the currency metric helps to indicate the real balance of a bank account that is presented to the user while being the same as the balance in the bank&#39;s database. The program that is being developed will focus more on this factor because of its compatibility with the cloud and fog servers.
- **Timeliness Factor:** This factor expresses the how old the data is since its creation. It is difficult to see why the age of the data may be appropriate for a given IoT device/application but the goal is to return data that is not too expired so that it can be read by modern software. The timeliness captures the gap between the data creation and the delivery of the data despite the date of the extraction. [CITATION Wan96 \l 2057]

## 3.5 - Time

There are many methods to data processing and how fast the data should be processed is completely dependent on the user and its purpose. Since the growth of the data in the modern age has expanded from various sources, more than ever is it important to analyse and processes this amount of data effectively. Understanding which data integration form the right option for a specific situation is an important step for ensuring that the data being processed is done in the fastest and least experience way[CITATION Sha14 \l 2057]. There are three forms of time processing speeds that are intended for different requirements:

- **Batch Processing:** it is well defined to be a form that involves collecting a series of data in bulk and processing it all simultaneously. This form is dedicated to large volumes of data that are processed at a daily, weekly, monthly and even yearly order. Instead of the data being transferred at a streamline basis, it is typically done through a schedule. For example, banks submit transactions over a course of a week, which include involves, payments and balance. Large volumes of data rely on the use of batch processing to transfer data hence why many large organisations utilize batch processing, which also reduces the operational costs and labour that is needed to support the data. It gives the organisational employees more control as to when to start the processing.
- **Real-Time Processing** : Since real-time holds very little disadvantages for being preferable to process data at a much quicker time whenever possible. The reaction with real time processing is guaranteed to happen in a matter of seconds or milliseconds. They are starting to be more encouraged in the modern age as IoT devices become more portable and heavily rely on data to be processed and received simultaneously, an example of this would be a heartbeat monitor watch which requires data to be sent to the server and received every second the heart beats. The data package is small, but the demand of data is high.
- **Near Real-Time Processing:** This processing criterion is commonly known to be the medium of batch and real-time processing. However, this is a common misinterpretation. It is technically a lower-demand version of real-time by being acceptable to process data within the minutes. An example of an algorithm that uses near real-time are those that detect violations on a website such as Facebook or Twitter. The content that is in violation tends to be posted in real-time, but it is then removed in near real-time by deciding that if it has violated a policy.

## 3.6 - Volume

The volume of the data amounts to sheer amount of data that needs to be processed. Fundamentally, there are two categorises that differ with each other: Big data which involves larger quantities of unstructured information that is too difficult for a lower-end system to process. Therefore, big data relies on large cloud servers to process the data and store it accordingly. The other category is small data, which is usually more precise bite-sized metrics that have one minor action or task. Since it is recognized that cloud computing has a higher reputation with dealing with large-volume big data than fog systems, it still helps for a fog system to use its close-proximity to support with analysing big data at a faster rate. This collaboration opens doors to ways the cloud and fog can communicate with each other to complete tasks in a more efficient and rapid way.

## 3.7 - Criticality

Critical data is identified by how precarious the data is needed to make an action function correctly. Usually, programs depend on a line of code the data provides to allow a program to function in its entirety. These types of data elements are always placed at the highest urgency and needs to be processed as priority #1. In the context of the organisation side, the criticality of data can be determined to be vital for the success of an organisation. For example, they could define the critical data as those that represent protected and personal information that are used in financial reports. These forms of data elements are identified as information of master data objects that are required for a decision-making process or that are used for measuring the performance of the organisation [CITATION Los08 \l 2057].

## 3.8 - Coordination &amp; Collaboration between Cloud and Fog

As discussed in the previous chapters, it is central to the paper to understand the advantages and disadvantages of cloud and fog. However, it is important to recognize that solely using fog or cloud independently will not always bring out the best results, thus the collaboration between them will need to be incorporated to bring out the fastest results with the best quality of service (&quot;QoS&quot;)6. By collaborating both of cloud and of fog&#39;s capabilities, the data processing can become seamless by leveraging the responsibilities to their respective machines (cloud to fog) or (fog to cloud). This kind of compatibility has become a viable method for many in the industry thanks to the advances in storage, processing and networking of the fog systems.

There are different cases when requesting and transmitting data, sometimes they may require independent systems (cloud/fog) but there is case were both systems can complement each other. For example, in a hazardous road, cars that contain fog nodes can collect information about the condition of the road and gain information such as potholes, weather, traffic etc. and transfer that information through the &quot;WAN&quot;7 until it reaches the cloud server, thus the cloud server can warn other drivers and suggest they avoid the road.





As shown by the example, the coordination between the systems not only assists people but may also save their lives. The relevance of these systems is becoming more transparent in people&#39;s lives and with the metrics that were mentioned in the above chapter will also help measure how these systems should interact with each other in the basis of processing data that is best in the extent of the QoS. The next step this paper aims to accomplish is to use these metrics to answer the question of how and in what order (cloud to fog, fog to cloud, fog or cloud) should data be sent/delivered from the IoT device (depending on the degree of the metrics). The creation of a software that helps to bring out the answer will also be developed and discussed.

# Chapter 4: Transactional Properties

## 4.1 - Introduction to Transactional Properties of Internet-of-Things

Internet of things or IoT are created to deliver on smart actions in some functionality. They deliver on their promise by sensing, actuating and delivering on complex tasks. The functionality can be encapsulated as a service and the task is executed by composing on those services. Since the &#39;things&#39; deliver on services such as sensing, actuating and communicating, they put them beyond the reach of other conventional oriented web services. Research has found that the same characteristics found in databases can also be intertwined IoT. These characteristics are the transactional properties (Atomicity, Pivot, Retriability, and Compensability) [CITATION KVi15 \l 2057]. In this research, the paper examines the relationship between IoT applications and how the transactional properties are applied.

The transactional properties are currently being used in many applications such as web services and databases. These properties allow users to view the execution behaviours of an application (if the process has been successful or has failed) (0:1). However, the behaviour of these processes can be a lot broader, as the execution of the task could fail but it must continue until success is achieved. These different behaviours lead the paper to discuss the different forms of transactional properties there are and how they determine success, failure and their termination conditions. To measure these determinations, the research considers the previous properties, which are: (pivot, compensatable &amp; retriable).

## 4.2 – Pivot

The pivot transactional property is said if it once successfully completes the effects that are produced remains permanent and cannot be semantically un-done. However, if the task fails, then it has no effect at all and cannot be done again. Generally, this is called a pivot but this research will move further to find an alternative to pivot that could increase its ratio of succession. As it is now, the pivot cannot be relied on for important tasks. This is especially compulsory because the pivot cannot be compensated either. Below shows the lifecycle of the pivot property with emphasis on each state.

Figure 1 - Original Pivot

## 4.3 – Compensatable

The compensatable property varies from the pivot task by if the effects after a successfully execution can be semantically undone. It is suggested that the compensation is an error-recovery mechanism. This property is particularly important for when a transaction is taking place that usually requires a long period to complete, if the task happens to fail, the other transactional properties such as a pivot may not be applicable to handle these long period errors. Hence being a recovery mechanism, compensatable is able to retry the transaction because it classes a transaction as a composition of a set of compensable transactions. Sequence and parallel are two standard primitives to put compensable transaction together into a larger compensable one [CITATION Jin07 \l 2057]. For a most illustrative view, the compensatable approach is displayed below:

Figure 2 – Compensatable

## 4.4 – Retriable

Retriable is one of the strongest transactional properties, meaning that it has the highest rate of success. This is because that the retriable property guarantees a successful termination after a finite number of invocations, this allows it to support forward recovery. So in assertion, the retriable property can be retired once or more times after failure. [CITATION Chr07 \l 2057] distinguishes it further by defining the property as a recovery mechanism which can be used if the failure of the retriable activity is without any consequences, so by way, the general effect of its failure does not influence the execution of the other activities, making this type of a neutral activity or idempotent, thus being able to be executed multiple times without any consequences. An example of this is shown below:



Figure 3 – Retriable

## 4.5 - Implementation of Transactional Properties

To implement the transactional properties into the IoT devices, the research must consider the different means in how the thing device performs its tasks. As it is known, the IoT device has three main properties (Sensing, Actuating &amp; Communicating) and to designate the appropriate properties for each one, we must consider them in single or combined entities. This is because different IoT devices utilize these three duties in different ways, some may use one and another may use two or three. Nevertheless, in the case of them being separate duties, they each all have their own appropriate property.

### 4.5.1 - Separate Duties

- **Sensing Duty**

- **Pivot** : The pivot property would not be applicable because if it fails, then it would dispose the IoT application from the sensed data to begin with.

- **Retriable** : The retriable property would be applicable because it can guarantee that the sensed data be available to the IoT application with precaution.

- **Compensatable** : For the case of compensatable, the sensing duty requires an absolute guarantee of success because of it being the first stage of the IoT device. The compensatable may not give it rate of success it requires because similar to the Pivot, the sensing failing is not applicable. Moreover, in the case of it cancelling (recalling/undoing) the sensed data, this should not be feasible way to attain it for the IoT.

#### - Actuating Duty

- **Pivot** : The pivot property would not be applicable because if it fails, then it would dispose the IoT application from actuating the data.

- **Retriable** : The retriable property would be applicable because it can guarantee that the data being actuated is successful. It can also go further by allowing the data to be actuated even more extensively.
- **Compensatable** : Compensatably actuation goes hand-in-hand well since it allows for the condition of data that has failed to be recalled in the sense of reversing what has been actuated.

#### - Communication Duty

- **Pivot** : The pivot property would not be applicable because if it fails, then it would dispose the IoT application from communication to outside parties.

- **Retriable** : The retriable property would be applicable because it can guarantee that the outside parties receive the communication

- **Compensatable** : being coupled with communication would be a failed scheme because if it fails and tries to recall what it is trying to communicate will be meaningless.

The table below lists the applicable transactional properties for each duty:

| **Pivot** | Inapplicable | Inapplicable | Inapplicable |
| **Retriable** | Applicable | Applicable | Applicable |
| **Compensatable** | Inapplicable | Applicable | Inapplicable |

In the chapter above, the paper discussed the duties as single entities that operate independently. However, this is not the majority of the case for many of the IoT devices. Most IoT applications cover at least two or all of the duties (Sensing, Actuating &amp; Communicating). In this case, the best way to decide on the applicable transactional property for full combinations, the research remedies the notion of full atomicity that is &quot;all or nothing&quot; property [CITATION Kri16 \l 2057]. This notion rules that even if a single duty fails, the entire combination falls with it. This examination tests to see if there is a single transactional property that is able to handle different combinations successfully. ## 4.6 - Introducing Strong Pivot

The outcome of the two tables above are very clear. The Pivot is absolute compared to compensatable and especially retriable which is able to correspond with entirely all of the duties (separate or otherwise). However, this discussion introduces a new concept called &#39;Strong Pivot&#39;, which is an upgraded version of the original pivot that uses only one cycle to finish its duty. To address the shortcoming of the original pivot, which is now coined as a &#39;Weak Pivot&#39;, the Strong Pivot supplements additional states to give the duty another chance of succession. Below illustrates the new and enhanced Strong Pivot:

Figure 4 - Strong Pivot

Just as the figure displays, the revised lifecycle is changed to add an additional procedure explicitly a precaution that if a duty would fail, there will be a second chance for the failed state to retry. The figure above illustrates this well by showing that once the duty is activated and has failed; there is an alternative duty that automatically takes place to retry the procedure. However, if both the main and alternative duties fail then the atomicity does not hold. In the implementation chapter, the research goes into detail in how the Strong Pivot takes its phase, and additionally a developed atomicity scenario demonstrates the difference between the Strong and Weak Pivots.

In conclusion, this chapter discussed the second segment of the research, which is based on the transactional properties within the IoT devices and how the IoT devices utilize their duties. By combining these duties to different forms of transactional properties, it would help treat the integrity of the data sent as paramount, it will also show what the best transactional property implemented would be preeminent for different IoT devices, particularly with the introduction to the new transactional model named as Strong Pivot which mitigates the effects of its predecessor model.

### 5.1.2 - Functional Requirements

The purpose of a functional requirement can be split into two views. The first one being that it should focus on the functions. In explicit terms; &#39;a function that a system must be able to perform&#39;[CITATION IEE90 \l 2057], &#39;what the product must do&#39;[CITATION Suz06 \l 2057], &#39;what the system should do&#39;[CITATION Som04 \l 2057]. The second view specifics the behaviour form of the requirement. This can be regarded as describing the behaviour aspects of the system [CITATION Ana97 \l 2057], those requirements that specify the inputs to the system, the responses (outputs) from the system and the behavioural relationships between them.

The program that is being developed serves as multi-criteria tool, which provides different services for this research. So in order to best manipulate the intelligent technologies to make the program as streamline as possible, it will provide an interactive menu, which seamlessly moves onto the other tabs when clicked. The main menu will serve as a hub where users can move around the services the program offers. It will also host a help button, which further assists those that need it. All these functional interactions are done with the speed of a button.

The system will provide an interactive slider whereas the user can drag their six criteria options for receiving their recommended answer from the program. This method if very distinct to the other ways of inputting information. The movement of the slider will be shown on text field that outputs the currently placed number of the slider. This is a very practical and pragmatic way of building the system, since the user can also enter in the required input instead of dragging the slider. Providing multiple means of inputting can enhance the user- experience and make it easier for different people. Once all the inputs are selected, the conditions will be automatically met and the system should output a recommendation after a button is selected. There is also a selection of other various functional inputs on the additional tabs. These include the use of button, browsing, sliders, combo boxes etc.

An important consideration is that the program should be able to handle incorrect or invalid input, for example only permitting the use of numbers in a text field. When an event of invalidity occurs, the system should automatically inform the user that this input is not supported and make it possible to provide guidance to the user to mitigate the error from happening again. This, to a degree brings forth the importance of a help menu. The program will possibly provide the user with instructions to how to use the program at a functional degree.

### 5.1.3 – Non-Functional Requirements

In contrast to the functional requirement, the non-functional specifics the system&#39;s properties, which include the constraints, implementation, performance, platform dependencies, extensibility, reliability and maintainability [CITATION Gru17 \l 2057]. Non-functional requirements will be considered to develop a successful program. In the case of the user experience, the user may not be ware of these requirements because it is handled in the backend of the domain, in contrast to the functional requirements that are often more criticized is understandable to be easier to elicit[CITATION Lui04 \l 2057].

### 5.1.4 - Performance Requirement

The performance requires the program to have a fast-response time and throughput. The program is being developed to take measure on these criteria&#39;s. The importance of the response time comes into the consideration of how patient the user is when using the program. Ultimately, a slow rate of response would be regarded as poor user-experience so to help push towards an improved rate of speed, the program will focus on having at least a minimum of 0.1 response time for tasks that require less demand on the software. The speed of 0.1 is warranted for the user to feel that the system is reacting instantaneously. This level of speed will be required when switching between windows. To do this, instead of Java opening multiple classes, the program will set the visibility on each panel through a click of a button – this is regarded as a sufficient way of loading all the elements at the first boot while also maintaining the speed of each window.

Optimization of the code is regarded as an efficient way to make the program run quickly. However, most programmers make trade-offs between how easy a program is to implement and maintain and how fast it runs. The program in development is a one-time creation as there would not necessary be any updates in the area of development; hence the program keeps in mind how fast it must run. Optimizations of code reduces large blocks of code and replaces them into smaller ones. This makes the program calculate what should be performed at a faster rate. With this understanding of processor operation, the program optimization should exploit the capability of processors to provide _instruction-level parallelism__10_ when executing multiple instructions simultaneously, this program will keep that in mind to take advantage over it and harness faster speeds.

### 5.1.5 – Reliability Requirement

The main objective that many developers must make is if the program will work under any possible condition. Any program can run quickly, but if it outputs incorrect results, it serves no real purpose - This comes in the heart of reliability. The program in development utilizes many multi-criteria decision tasks, thus the &#39;_if-statement&#39;_ _11_will be used greatly to help make these decisions. This form of statement is considered very reliable since the programmer inputs the verified options only. It has been stated that 99% of flow decisions are made with &#39;_if&#39;_ and is a top method for many developers to utilize. The program will also include an option to cancel a current operation, giving the system a way to exit from one task and run another, this making it even less error-prone. There is also the aspect of reliability in portability. The system should be designed to cater towards different systems in different locations to help facilitate as many users as possible.

### 5.1.6 – Conclusion of Requirement Analysis

Functional requirements are branded by the basic operations or core that a program is expected to deliver. While the non-functional requirement includes factors such as how the system scale is or if it can adapt different loads while being invulnerable to bugs that may harm the performance… In conclusion, the saga for the system must entail well-demonstrated requirements that were listed above to determine the overall success of the product. The listed requirements that were mentioned in this chapter should be incorporated into the final design of the software while also respecting the guidelines of LSEP (Legal, Social Ethical and Professional) standards.

## 5.2 – Introduction to Design Phase

The design phase discusses the overall design and concepts that have been developed with the software. As told by [CITATION IEE90a \l 2057], the design phase is both &quot;the process defining the architecture, components, interfaces and other characteristics of a system or component.&quot; In addition, &quot;the result of [that] process&quot; is viewed as another form of process within the software development life cycle where the software requirements are analysed to produce a portrayal of the internal structure of the program. Another purpose of this chapter is consider the overall architecture of the system and why it was developed for that reason. Below will go through the formation of the program by its life cycle in a design-specific orientation.

### 5.2.1 - Preliminary Design Phase

Before beginning the design of the software, there was exhaustive planning to undergo the final design, this includes a major design overhaul the program had to go through. The phases that took until the completion of the program had to keep in mind how visually appearing the program should become while being simple to navigate through. These steps were taken before the initiation of the program as shown in the appendices at the end of this paper (Appendix 1, 2, 3, 4, 5). These also included the requirements that were identified in the previous chapter to be incorporated in the final design. Figure 5 - Use Case Diagram of Software

### 5.2.2 - Interface Design

In addition to designing the actual architecture of the program, it is also important to create an eye-catching design that is well constructed and works functionality. The system design can sometimes be the make or break of the software. There are those who judge a system entirely by its interface rather than the functionality. A poorly designed interface can cause the user to make mistakes and errors then lead to the software to never be used. To overcome this, the design made certain to follow these steps:

- **Consistency** : This characteristic is an important aspect of user interface. It shows that the design was created in a certain pattern, and doing so will allow users to understand the pattern and quickly so they can interact more seamlessly. Having consist colours, buttons, languages and other elements make the user feel more comfortable. They would feel that the program was designed, arranged and filled with logical information that they know how to navigate to.
- **Navigation** : Without easily navigable elements, the program can appear unstructured and unorganised. The program was designed to keep the navigation as simple as possible so the users would be able to explore the program without finding any hidden treasure.
- **Simplicity** : The &#39;Multi-Criteria&#39; program followed a layout of simplicity. The purpose of this is to avoid any interfering colours, elements to help the audience see clearly, what the software offers without any confusion. When it comes to user-friendliness, keeping everything simple can be a big contributor to maintaining clarity for all age groups.
